[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, G, M, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(120/7);
B = dir(0);
C = dir(-120/7);
D = dir(-240/7);
E = dir(-360/7);
F = dir(-480/7);
G = dir(-600/7);
M = (A + B + D)/3;

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--D--cycle);
draw(O--M);
draw(O--G);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, E);
label("$C$", C, S);
label("$D$", D, W);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", F, SE);
label("$G$", G, NE);
label("$M$", M, NW);
label("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $GOM$,
\[\cos \angle GOM = \frac{OG^2 + OM^2 - GM^2}{2 \cdot OG \cdot OM}.\]Since $ABCDEFG$ is a regular heptagon, $OG = 1$.  Also, $OM = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD = \frac{AD}{3}$.

Let $x = AD$.  Then by the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABD$,
\[x^2 = x^2 + x^2 - 2 \cdot x \cdot x \cdot \cos \frac{360^\circ}{7}.\]Hence, $\cos \frac{360^\circ}{7} = \frac{1}{2}$.

Again by the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABD$,
\[BD^2 = x^2 + x^2 - 2 \cdot x \cdot x \cdot \cos \frac{240^\circ}{7} = 2x^2 + 2x^2 \cos \frac{120^\circ}{7}.\]Since $M$ is the centroid of triangle $ABD$, $GM = \frac{2}{3} \cdot BD = \frac{2}{3} \sqrt{2x^2 + 2x^2 \cos \frac{120^\circ}{7}}$.

Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\cos \angle GOM &= \frac{1^2 + \left( \frac{x}{3} \right)^2 - \left( \frac{2}{3} \sqrt{2x^2 + 2x^2 \cos \frac{120^\circ}{7}} \right)^2}{2 \cdot 1 \cdot \frac{x}{3}} \\
&= \frac{9 + x^2 - 8x^2 - 8x^2 \cos \frac{120^\circ}{7}}{6x} \\
&= \frac{9 - 7x^2 - 8x^2 \cos \frac{120^\circ}{7}}{6x}.
\end{align*}Since $\cos \frac{120^\circ}{7} = \frac{1}{2}$,
\[\cos \angle GOM = \frac{9 - 7x^2 - 4x^2}{6x} = \frac{9 - 11x^2}{6x}.\]Then
\[\cos^2 \angle GOM = \frac{81 - 198x^2 + 121x^4}{36x^2}.\]Since $x = AD$ is the side length of the heptagon, $x$ is positive, so we can cancel $x^2$ from the numerator and denominator, to get
\[\cos^2 \angle GOM = \boxed{\frac{81 - 198x^2 + 121x^4}{36}}.\]

